Semilarski vs Prosecutor’s Office: Former Deputy Mayor of Tartu to be cassed on August 4
This means that a decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the two first instances refused to consider Semilarski’s claim, but in April his cassation appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its resolution did not fall within its jurisdiction.
The court ' s ruling stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the county court should regulate such matters,” Anette Kreitsmann, a spokeswoman for the Tartu courts, told ERR earlier.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the state will have to say its word.
According to Semilarski’s lawyer, juror Oliver Nyas, his client was unreasonably suspected of bribery for about two years.
He now demands that the prosecutor’s office refute the false allegations against him and compensate him for the moral damage.
The reason for filing a complaint to the court were the statements of the Prosecutor for Special Cases of the Lyuna District Prosecutor’s Office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, along with the other Deputy Mayor of Tartu, Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
“When I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu, one of the most influential local governments, were corrupt.
These public suspicions hung in the air accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to say anything about it,” Semilarski said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyas, at the press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework within which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The allegation of bribery and corruption turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, representatives of the state should be careful in choosing words so that suspects would not be presented as criminals before the verdict.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, has not been observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” said Nees.
“The public representation of Semilarski as a serious offender and bribe-taker in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being established is unacceptable, which is contrary to the presumption of innocence and unfair to the applicant,” the lawyer added.
According to rus.err.ee, the former deputy mayor of Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be prosecuted on bribery charges - the criminal case initiated against him in July was partially closed.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu more than thirty times participated in meetings of the city administration when making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated at a personal level during off-hours.
According to Gross, in all these cases Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to withdraw from participation in decision-making.
Earlier, according to rus.err.ee, the prosecutor’s office presented Semilarsky with suspicions of receiving bribes and violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor, Artem Suvorov (Center Party).
At that time, the prosecutor’s office and the security police said that there was strong evidence against both deputy mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
The Suvorov case later reached the court, which fully justified the politician.
The trial of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
