How the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to lower the key rate again.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage points, to 4.25% per annum - formally the next historical low.
Judging by the return of the short step of lowering the rate, as well as the tone of the statements of the Central Bank and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistic than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary easing may soon come to a halt.
“We have continued to ease monetary policy, primarily considering that the risks of inflation deviating down from 4% in 2021 still remain,” said Elvira Nabiullina, head of the Bank of Russia.
They are associated with a significant decline in economic activity, a fall in domestic and external demand.
The economic recovery, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes have revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand have recovered, construction and production of consumer goods have expanded, the annual rate of decrease in cargo turnover of transport and industrial production has slowed.
According to the updated forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the economic contraction will be 4.5-5.5% (previously it was expected 4-6%), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised its forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the Central Bank expected $ 27 and $ 35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The view of the Bank of Russia on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the easing cycle, according to economists for Russia and the CIS "Renaissance Capital" Sophia Donetsk and Andrei Melashchenko.
Thus, the Bank of Russia has consistently lowered the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it immediately by one percentage point due to low inflation rates due to depressed demand and the need to stimulate the slowing economy due to the pandemic and related restrictions.
The chances of further adjustment of monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is close, agrees the chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The combination of pro-inflationary risks also points to the imminence of a pause in interest-rate easing – disrupted supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures, and a faster (compared to expectations) demand recovery, he says.
In addition, the Bank of Russia’s subsequent actions will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts.
One way or another, the reduction of the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, perhaps, on the mortgage, says senior economist of the analytical management of the bank "Otkritie" Maxim Petronevych.
The correction of rates will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he clarifies.
The rates on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude the economist "BCS Premier" Anton Pokatovich.
Average deposit rates, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they may fall to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
