Rwandan man confesses to setting fire to Nantes cathedral
A Rwandan man who worked at Saints Peter and Paul's Cathedral in Nantes, France, confessed to arson a week after the fire.
This is reported on Sunday by France 3 TV channel.
According to him, the man, who had already been detained on July 19, the day after the fire, was arrested again the day before.
On Saturday night, he appeared before the investigating judge.
After being charged with intentional damage to property, the man admitted that he organized arson in three places - under a large organ, under a small organ and at the electric shield.
He now faces up to 10 years in prison and a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 fine.
The motives of the 39-year-old from Rwanda have not yet been disclosed.
It is only known that he voluntarily helped in the cathedral and on the day of the fire had to close its doors.
However, according to CCTV footage, he left the religious institution 15 minutes after receiving calls about a fire in the building.
The fire in the Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul occurred on July 18.
More than 200 firefighters fought for several hours for the monument of Gothic architecture.
However, they failed to save the stained glass of the time of Louis XII and the unique organ of the Baroque era.
The situation was not brought under control until three hours after the fire started.
No one was injured as a result of the incident.
The current fire is not the first during the existence of the temple.
In 1972, a fire destroyed his roof.
It took 13 years to eliminate the effects of the fire.
The cathedral was reopened to parishioners only in 1985.
