The actor of the Russian series responded to accusations of “propaganda of LGBT and feminism”
The actor of the Russian series “Chicks”, whose creators were accused of “propaganda of LGBT and feminism”, responded to the claims to the film.
The authors “understood the severity of the topics raised and did not want to offend anyone,” said American Stephen Thomas Oxner in an interview with the publication “Lift”.
“It seems to me that this is a story about the power and general aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the boy’s father, who was dressed in women’s clothing.
He stressed that he is "proud of the work" and does not consider it propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he is afraid of the reaction of some people to the storyline of the series: for example, there was a case when "a man in deep drunkenness shot the set and said that all this is not true."
“Then there were a couple of cases where we met dissatisfied locals who did not understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so people who first came with complaints began to help us,” he concluded.
The incident with the shooting, explains the publication, occurred in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunken man attacked the car of the film crew with a weapon, after which he was detained by police officers.
